{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"alias":"wall-marlin-filth","description":"## Reproduction Steps\n\n1. Open a PR; CI runs the default pytest suite across the matrix (ubuntu/macos × py3.11/3.12).\n2. On a loaded runner (observed on `macos-latest, py3.12`), `tests/scripts/graph/test_graph_perf.py` fails on absolute wall-clock assertions even though the code is unchanged.\n\nObserved failures (PR #108 run 28505746020):\n- `test_graph_perf.py:59` — `build_dep_graph took 3.192s for 1,000-ticket chain (limit: 2.0s)`\n- `test_graph_perf.py:327` — `9 cross-tier add_dependency calls took 8.65s (limit: 5.0s)`\n\nBoth passed on all ubuntu runners in the same PR; a manual re-run of the macOS job passed. So the failures are runner-load-dependent, not a code regression.\n\n## Expected vs Actual\n\n- **Expected:** perf tests gate against genuine algorithmic regressions and are stable across CI runners.\n- **Actual:** they assert against fixed absolute-time thresholds (`< 2.0s`, `< 5.0s`) that a slow/loaded shared runner (esp. macOS) blows past, producing false-failure PR blocks that require manual re-runs.\n\n## Impact\n\nFlaky red on unrelated PRs → wasted re-runs + eroded trust in the gate (a green PR gets blocked by an infra hiccup). This blocked epic 3156's final merge (PR #108) until a manual re-run.\n\n## Root cause\n\nAbsolute wall-clock budgets are sensitive to shared-runner contention. A perf test should measure a *relative* signal (scaling / ratio vs a baseline op on the same machine) or run in an isolated, non-gating, retried context — not a raw seconds ceiling.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `tests/scripts/graph/test_graph_perf.py` no longer false-fails under runner load: either (a) assert on a RELATIVE metric (e.g. per-op time scaled to a same-machine baseline, or big-O scaling ratio between N and 2N) instead of an absolute seconds ceiling, or (b) mark the wall-clock assertions with a bounded retry (e.g. `flaky`/rerun) AND widen the ceilings with generous headroom, or (c) move the raw-timing assertions to a dedicated NON-gating perf job (still run, reported, not merge-blocking) while keeping a correctness-only assertion in the gating suite.\n- [ ] The chosen approach still catches a real >2x algorithmic regression (a deliberately O(n^2) reintroduction fails the test) — documented in the test.\n- [ ] No absolute single-run wall-clock ceiling remains in the gating path for these two tests.","id":"edfe-d8cd-5f19-46f2","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"bug","title":"Flaky graph perf tests (absolute wall-clock limits) fail on loaded CI runners"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1782904824498279001,"uuid":"3e2a4cf0-76a8-47b4-8d78-8758042b6a00"}